Identifying & Addressing Accessibility Issues on a Website

Throughout the Testing Accessibility workshop series, you’ll work with a demo web app called CampSpots.

This is the website for a fictional camping-themed site that includes a number of pages.

There are several intentional accessibility issues included in the application, all based on real examples I’ve encountered in the field.

🛠 Challenge: Find Accessibility Issues using Keyboard-Only Navigation

Your first challenge will be to identify potential issues on the CampSpots Careers Portal using only the keyboard.

As you work through this challenge, ask yourself:

How efficiently can someone navigate the site with only the keyboard? Would someone be able to complete their task?

Navigate with the Keyboard

Navigating a website with the keyboard primarily requires a few keys.

The following keyboard commands are fundamental to navigating the web:

  • Tab to go forward through interactive elements
  • Shift + Tab to go backwards
  • Spacebar to scroll down (Shift + Space to scroll up)
  • Enter to submit forms and activate widgets
  • The arrow keys
    • Up and down to scroll the page
    • Left, right, up, and down to navigate through some form controls and custom-scripted widgets

Use these keys to navigate on through the Careers Portal page and find accessibility issues.

Accessing the CampSpots Careers Portal

You can access the CampSpots Careers Portal via the deployed site or in a local dev environment.

To run the site locally you will need to clone and follow the README: https://github.com/testing-accessibility/workshop-design-people-skills

Go Further with Chrome’s Developer Tools

If you want to take the challenge a bit further, try inspecting the page’s markup with Chrome’s Developer Tools.

In case you aren’t familiar with DevTools, here are a couple of ways to open them:

  • At the top right corner of the Chrome window, click on three vertical dots to open a dropdown menu. Click on ”More tools”, then “Developer Tools”.
  • Use a keyboard shortcut. Mac users can use Command + Option + C and Windows users can use Ctrl + Shift + C.

🛠Solution: Find Accessibility Issues using Keyboard-Only Navigation

As you hit the Tab key on a page, focus will shift to the next item you can interact with.

Despite the amount of information on the Career Portals page, it only has two places where the Tab key will take you on the page before bringing focus up to the location bar in the browser.

It’s also not clear where the focus has gone!

The status bar in the lower left corner of the browser will display the address of any links focused by the user. In the Careers Portal, the Tab key is finding links to a licensing related page and a legal related page but it’s not visibly clear where those links are.

The keyboard doesn’t take the user to the account dropdown in the upper right of the screen.

Using the mouse to open the menu, we can see several options that should be keyboard accessible.

Also, notice the links to “Licensing” and “Terms of service”– these are the places where the Tab key was reaching.

Although the menu appeared to be visibly closed, on the development side of things its contents weren’t hidden properly.

These are both keyboard interactivity issues.

Someone using the keyboard will not be able to interact with this web page.

If you examined the Careers Portal dashboard with DevTools, you'll notice that it is div elements all the way down.

Unfortunately, this lack of semantic structure is not uncommon.

🛠 Challenge: Find Low Contrast Text Issues using Chrome DevTools

Some people with low vision have trouble distinguishing digital text and graphical objects when certain color combinations are used.

A contrast ratio measures the difference in brightness between the foreground and background colors of a web page.

If the colors on your site have a low enough contrast ratio, low vision users may literally experience your site as a blank screen!

For this challenge, make a list of what you suspect are color contrast issues on the Careers Portal.

Go Further with DevTools

Chrome Developer Tools has a feature that will show us the measured contrast ratio between two colors you can pick off the page with a dropper tool.

To measure text contrast in DevTools, follow these steps:

  1. Click the Elements tab.
  2. Select the text-based element that you want to inspect.
  3. In the Styles pane, click the color square next to the element's color value.
  4. Check the Contrast Ratio section of the Color Picker.

Note: occasionally the contrast tool in Chrome will not show in the color picker for unclear reasons. In this scenario, make notes of color values for foreground and background colors and test in another tool like the WebAIM Contrast Analyzer.

🛠 Solution: Find Low Contrast Ratio Issues using Chrome DevTools

The Careers Portal has several contrast issues present on the page.

There are multiple places where the light gray text on white background isn’t sufficient. The gray on blue combination isn’t good enough either!

Measuring Contrast using Chrome DevTools

First, inspect the blue Details link on the dashboard using DevTools.

Notice that the styles pane shows us a contrast ratio of 2.74:1 (read as 2.74 to 1) and a “no” icon.

Compare this to the recommended WCAG AA level of 4.5:1.

We need to come up with a different color!

A color that meets contrast recommendations will show one green checkmark if it meets the AA level, and two green checkmarks if it meets AAA.

Other Color Contrast Issues

Sometimes you can follow your gut instincts about other potential contrast issues (this depends on eyesight and color perception, too!).

For non-text contrast on things like graphical controls and data visualizations, it’s often a case of neighboring colors more than foreground and background.

The big circular chart on the Careers Portal page features shades of green and blue that would be hard for some users to distinguish.

Lesson Recap

The main takeaway is that discovering issues is only the start: you also want to feel confident those issues will have real user impact and not land in a sea of design and technical debt. Part of this process involves developing your ability to communicate compelling issues with potential solutions so that they gain traction in the software development cycle.

I want you to consider the following two questions:

What is at stake for people with disabilities when they can’t use a site or application?

How should these issues be addressed through product, design, and development?

Answering these questions will help you formulate a cohesive solution that can be communicated effectively across your team and organization.
